,"Slovenian: nickname from an old spelling of the archaic adjective <i>maren</i> meaning ‘diligent’, but also ‘worthless’. Compare   Maren  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]},{"name":"Nicolao","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicolas de Mearns was born about 1175, in Scotland. She married Nicolas de Mearns in 1190, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1175–":"umbes 1175–Surnud","1170–1203":"1170–1203","1195–1262":"1195–1262","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1175":"1175","1262":"1262","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","about 1175":"umbes 1175","Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1175–":"noin 1175–Kuollut","1170–1203":"1170–1203","1195–1262":"1195–1262","1175–Female":"1175–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1175":"1175","1262":"1262","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","about 1175":"noin 1175","Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fr":{"about 1175–":"environ 1175–Décédée","1170–1203":"1170–1203","1195–1262":"1195–1262","1175–Female":"1175–Décédée","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1175":"1175","1262":"1262","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","about 1175":"environ 1175","Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicolas de Mearns est née environ 1175, à Écosse. Elle a épousé Nicolas de Mearns en 1190, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1175–":"um 1175–Verstorben","1170–1203":"1170–1203","1195–1262":"1195–1262","1175–Female":"1175–Verstorben","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1175":"1175","1262":"1262","1195":"1195","1170":"1170","about 1175":"um 1175","Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Nicolas de Mearns wurde um 1175 in Scotland geboren. Sie hat 1190 in Scotland Nicolas de Mearns geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1175–":"about 1175–Desede","1170–1203":"1170–1203","1195–1262":"1195–1262","1175–Female":"1175–Desede","1190":"1190","1203":"1203","1175":"1175","1